{
  "What is acceleration?": "",
  "The rate of change of distance": "",
  "The rate of change of velocity with respect to time": "",
  "The total displacement": "",
  "The speed of an object": "",
  "Acceleration is the rate at which velocity changes over time: a = change in velocity / change in time. It is a vector quantity with both magnitude and direction.": "",
  "What is the SI unit of acceleration?": "",
  "N": "",
  "m/s": "",
  "m/s^2": "",
  "kg*m/s": "",
  "The SI unit of acceleration is meters per second squared (m/s^2). This means the velocity changes by a certain number of m/s every second.": "",
  "What does the slope of a velocity-time graph represent?": "",
  "Acceleration": "",
  "Velocity": "",
  "Force": "",
  "Displacement": "",
  "The slope of a velocity-time graph equals the change in velocity divided by the change in time, which is acceleration. A positive slope means speeding up; a negative slope means slowing down.": "",
  "What does the area under a velocity-time graph represent?": "",
  "Speed": "",
  "The area under a velocity-time graph equals the displacement of the object. For simple shapes like rectangles and triangles, use basic geometry to calculate the area.": "",
  "Can an object have zero velocity but nonzero acceleration?": "",
  "Only for very heavy objects": "",
  "Yes, like a ball at the top of its trajectory": "",
  "Only in outer space": "",
  "No, that is impossible": "",
  "Yes. A ball thrown upward has zero velocity at its peak, but gravity still accelerates it downward at 9.8 m/s^2. Velocity and acceleration are independent quantities.": "",
  "If you double the net force on an object (constant mass), acceleration:": "",
  "Doubles": "",
  "Quadruples": "",
  "Stays the same": "",
  "Halves": "",
  "From Newton's second law (F = ma), if mass is constant and force doubles, acceleration doubles. Acceleration is directly proportional to net force.": "",
  "Is acceleration a scalar or a vector?": "",
  "Neither": "",
  "Vector": "",
  "Both": "",
  "Scalar": "",
  "Acceleration is a vector quantity because it has both magnitude (how much the velocity changes per second) and direction (in which direction the velocity changes).": "",
  "A car goes from 0 to 20 m/s in 5 seconds. What is its acceleration?": "",
  "100 m/s^2": "",
  "4 m/s^2": "",
  "25 m/s^2": "",
  "15 m/s^2": "",
  "Acceleration = change in velocity / time = (20 - 0) / 5 = 20/5 = 4 m/s^2. The car's speed increases by 4 m/s each second.": "",
  "What does negative acceleration (deceleration) mean?": "",
  "The object is moving backward in every situation": "",
  "The object is not accelerating at all currently": "",
  "The acceleration is in the direction opposite to the velocity": "",
  "The object has no velocity at this moment in time": "",
  "Negative acceleration (deceleration) means the acceleration is directed opposite to the velocity, causing the object to slow down. It does not necessarily mean the object is moving backward.": "",
  "What is the acceleration of an object moving at constant velocity?": "",
  "9.8 m/s^2": "",
  "Speed-dependent": "",
  "Zero m/s^2": "",
  "Same as velocity": "",
  "If velocity is constant (not changing), then acceleration = 0 m/s^2. Acceleration only exists when there is a change in velocity.": "",
  "What does the term 'deceleration' mean?": "",
  "Acceleration that causes an object to slow down over a period of time": "",
  "Acceleration that causes an object to speed up in a forward direction": "",
  "The complete absence of any acceleration acting on a moving object": "",
  "Acceleration that occurs only when an object is in free fall downward": "",
  "Deceleration is acceleration that opposes the direction of motion, causing the object to slow down. It is not a separate physical concept from acceleration; it just describes acceleration that reduces speed.": "",
  "What does 'constant acceleration' mean?": "",
  "Velocity increases by the same amount during each equal time interval": "",
  "The object moves at the same speed throughout the entire journey": "",
  "Velocity stays the same because the acceleration does not change it": "",
  "The force on the object changes at a constant rate over time": "",
  "Constant acceleration means the velocity changes by the same amount in every equal time interval. For example, if acceleration is 3 m/s^2, velocity increases by 3 m/s every second.": "",
  "What does 'average acceleration' mean?": "",
  "The total change in velocity divided by the total time interval": "",
  "The maximum acceleration reached during a period of time": "",
  "The arithmetic mean of all forces acting on the object at once": "",
  "The acceleration measured only at the midpoint of a time interval": "",
  "Average acceleration = (final velocity - initial velocity) / time elapsed. It tells you the overall rate of velocity change over a given time interval.": "",
  "What does 'instantaneous acceleration' mean?": "",
  "The acceleration of an object at a specific moment in time": "",
  "The total acceleration accumulated over the entire trip duration": "",
  "The acceleration that occurs the instant an object comes to rest": "",
  "The initial acceleration an object has when it first starts moving": "",
  "Instantaneous acceleration is the acceleration at a specific moment in time. On a velocity-time graph, it equals the slope of the tangent line at that particular point.": "",
  "What is the difference between 'acceleration' and 'velocity'?": "",
  "Velocity describes how fast position changes; acceleration describes how fast velocity changes": "",
  "Velocity is a vector and acceleration is a scalar physical quantity": "",
  "They are two words that describe exactly the same physical concept": "",
  "Velocity applies only to horizontal motion; acceleration applies only to vertical": "",
  "Velocity is the rate of change of position (how fast and in what direction something moves). Acceleration is the rate of change of velocity (how quickly velocity itself changes). Both are vectors.": "",
  "What does 'uniform acceleration' describe?": "",
  "Motion where the speed stays the same but direction keeps changing": "",
  "Motion where the acceleration remains constant over time": "",
  "Motion where the object accelerates only during the first half of the trip": "",
  "Motion where all objects in a group accelerate at the same rate together": "",
  "Uniform acceleration means the acceleration stays constant (does not change with time). Free fall near Earth's surface is an example of uniform acceleration (g = 9.8 m/s^2 = constant).": "",
  "What does 'non-uniform acceleration' mean?": "",
  "Acceleration that changes in magnitude or direction over time": "",
  "Acceleration that always has a magnitude of exactly 9.8 m/s^2": "",
  "Acceleration that only occurs when objects are moving very slowly": "",
  "Acceleration that applies only to objects in circular orbital motion": "",
  "Non-uniform acceleration means the acceleration itself changes over time. For example, a car that presses the gas pedal harder and harder has increasing (non-uniform) acceleration.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'centripetal acceleration'?": "",
  "Acceleration directed toward the center of a circular path": "",
  "Acceleration that acts in the same direction as the object's velocity": "",
  "Acceleration that pushes objects away from the center of a circle": "",
  "Acceleration that only occurs when objects move in a straight line": "",
  "Centripetal acceleration points toward the center of a circular path and is responsible for changing the direction of velocity during circular motion. It does not change the speed.": "",
  "What does 'gravitational acceleration' (g) represent?": "",
  "The acceleration caused by gravity near Earth's surface, about 9.8 m/s^2 downward": "",
  "The acceleration that only applies to objects that are heavier than 1 kilogram": "",
  "The acceleration experienced only by objects that are already in free fall": "",
  "The velocity at which all objects fall to the ground regardless of their mass": "",
  "Gravitational acceleration (g) is the acceleration due to Earth's gravity, approximately 9.8 m/s^2 directed downward. It applies to all objects near Earth's surface, regardless of mass.": "",
  "What does the phrase 'change in velocity' represent in the acceleration formula?": "",
  "Final velocity minus initial velocity, which can be positive or negative": "",
  "The total distance traveled divided by the total time of travel": "",
  "The absolute value of the velocity at any given moment in time": "",
  "The sum of the initial and final velocities added together": "",
  "Change in velocity (delta v) = final velocity - initial velocity. It can be positive (speeding up in the positive direction) or negative (slowing down or reversing). It is the numerator in the acceleration formula.": "",
  "A car traveling at 30 m/s brakes and comes to a stop in 6 seconds. What is the car's acceleration?": "",
  "-5 m/s^2": "",
  "+5 m/s^2": "",
  "-180 m/s^2": "",
  "+30 m/s^2": "",
  "Acceleration = (final velocity - initial velocity) / time = (0 - 30) / 6 = -30/6 = -5 m/s^2. The negative sign indicates the car is decelerating (slowing down).": "",
  "A student observes a ball rolling down a ramp and notices it covers 1 m in the first second, 3 m in the second second, and 5 m in the third second. Is the ball accelerating?": "",
  "No, because it moves in a straight line the entire time": "",
  "Yes, because it covers increasing distances in equal time intervals": "",
  "No, because the ball is rolling and not falling freely downward": "",
  "Yes, but only during the first second of its motion down the ramp": "",
  "The ball covers increasing distances in equal time intervals (1 m, 3 m, 5 m), which means its speed is increasing. An increasing speed means the ball is accelerating.": "",
  "A skateboarder accelerates from 2 m/s to 8 m/s in 3 seconds. What is the skateboarder's acceleration?": "",
  "3 m/s^2": "",
  "2 m/s^2": "",
  "6 m/s^2": "",
  "10 m/s^2": "",
  "Acceleration = (8 - 2) / 3 = 6/3 = 2 m/s^2. The skateboarder's velocity increases by 2 m/s each second.": "",
  "In a lab, a student records that a cart on a track has a velocity of 1.0 m/s at t = 0 s and 4.0 m/s at t = 2 s. If the acceleration is constant, what is the velocity at t = 1 s?": "",
  "3.0 m/s": "",
  "2.0 m/s": "",
  "2.5 m/s": "",
  "1.5 m/s": "",
  "Acceleration = (4.0 - 1.0) / 2 = 1.5 m/s^2. At t = 1 s: v = 1.0 + 1.5(1) = 2.5 m/s. With constant acceleration, velocity increases uniformly.": "",
  "A bicycle slows from 15 m/s to 5 m/s over 10 seconds. What is the bicycle's average acceleration?": "",
  "+1 m/s^2": "",
  "-1 m/s^2": "",
  "+2 m/s^2": "",
  "-2 m/s^2": "",
  "Acceleration = (5 - 15) / 10 = -10/10 = -1 m/s^2. The negative sign indicates the bicycle is decelerating (slowing down).": "",
  "A student drops a ball from rest. After 3 seconds of free fall (ignoring air resistance), what is the ball's velocity?": "",
  "About 9.8 m/s downward": "",
  "About 19.6 m/s downward": "",
  "About 29.4 m/s downward": "",
  "About 44.1 m/s downward": "",
  "v = u + at = 0 + (9.8)(3) = 29.4 m/s downward. In free fall, velocity increases by 9.8 m/s each second.": "",
  "A car accelerates at 3 m/s^2 from rest. How fast is it going after 4 seconds?": "",
  "7 m/s": "",
  "12 m/s": "",
  "0.75 m/s": "",
  "48 m/s": "",
  "v = u + at = 0 + (3)(4) = 12 m/s. Starting from rest (u = 0) with constant acceleration, the speed increases linearly with time.": "",
  "A roller coaster car speeds up from 5 m/s to 25 m/s in 4 seconds, then maintains 25 m/s for the next 6 seconds. What is the average acceleration over the entire 10 seconds?": "",
  "5 m/s^2": "",
  "2.5 m/s^2": "",
  "0 m/s^2": "",
  "Average acceleration = (final velocity - initial velocity) / total time = (25 - 5) / 10 = 20/10 = 2 m/s^2. The constant-velocity phase reduces the average acceleration over the full 10 seconds.": "",
  "A student throws a ball upward at 20 m/s. How long does it take to reach its highest point? (Use g = 10 m/s^2 for simplicity.)": "",
  "1 second": "",
  "2 seconds": "",
  "4 seconds": "",
  "10 seconds": "",
  "At the highest point, v = 0. Using v = u + at: 0 = 20 + (-10)t, so t = 20/10 = 2 seconds. Gravity decelerates the ball at 10 m/s^2 until it momentarily stops.": "",
  "A train moving at 20 m/s applies brakes and decelerates at 2 m/s^2. A student asks how long it takes to stop. What is the answer?": "",
  "5 seconds": "",
  "20 seconds": "",
  "40 seconds": "",
